deployment  prior to proceeding to final deployment of the model it is important to thoroughly evaluate the model and review the steps executed to create the model in order to be certain the model properly achieves the business objectives.   monitoring  with monitoring, you generate more data and then you can feed it back to your original data or build new models.  this is a cyclical process and can lead you to examine other questions or solve other data mining problems.    evaluation  prior to proceeding to final deployment of the model it is important to thoroughly evaluate the model and review the steps executed to create the model in order to be certain the model properly achieves the business objectives.   modeling use one or multiple modelling techniques by specifying and calibrating parameters to optimal values.  some techniques require data in specific formats, hence, iterative data preparation is necessary. once you're done with creating and running your model, you go to model evaluation and validation.   data preparation   the data preparation phase covers all activities needed to construct the final dataset, data that will be fed into the modeling tools, from the initial raw data.  tasks include, table, record and attribute selection, as well as transformation and cleaning of data for modeling tools.    data understanding  starts with initial data collection proceeds with activities that enable data scientists to become familiar with the data, identify data quality problems, discover first insights into the data, and detect interesting subsets to form hypotheses regarding hidden information.   business understanding  understanding the project objectives and requirements  the more you understand the business, the more it helps you understand the data    click on each part of the crisp-dm to examine the components

notesData.content: >Chapter 2: Introduction to Data Science
>The era of Big Data is awakening companies to the opportunities to use data for competitive advantage.
>These approaches predominantly use tools such as spreadsheets, database queries and other business intelligence tools.
>There is increasing interest in methods for extracting meaningful information and knowledge from Big Data for use in decision making.
>Powerful computers and computer networks, internet technologies, high volumes of data and efficient algorithms
> have given rise to data science principles and data mining techniques with the ultimate goal to improve
>and speed up the decision making process.
>In this Chapter we will examine the topics:
>What is Data Science?
>Data Science considerations
>and using CRISP-DM as a strategy for Data Mining
>What is data science?
>There is a myth that people say it's a computer-driven process that looks for patterns in huge complex database and automatically gives the result.
>But the fact is that it's actually user-driven, utilized by computers.
>There's no shortcut.
>Softwares like Knowledge Studio make this easy.
>The first thing we need to consider is our data.
>Data is the most valuable business asset and it's a prerequisite to data science.
>We need to make sure that we have enough data and that we have access to the data.
>We also need to understand where the data is located such as in electronic format, PDF format or HTML.
>We also need to think about how we can convert unstructured data to structured data.
>We need to check that our data covers the relevant factors that we need to solve our problem.
>We need understand how noisy our data is, for example how much missing data is there, and do we have enough data.
>For example, do you have all groups for a certain variable in your data?
>If you don't have access to all of them there may be some under-represented variables at the time of training that model.

>Expertise on data is also important. Lets say there is a specific field in your data such as payment which has been created by an auto-dialer, and there is another flag that identifies if the payment was actually made or not.
>So, if you don't know about that flag, we might just use the payment field in our model, which is not true based on the flag.
>Understanding also helps explain the result better.
>To guide your project, answer the following questions:
>What substantive problem do you want to solve?
>What data are available, and what parts are relevant?
>What kind of pre-processing & cleaning is needed before starting?
>For example, is there missing values and what is their identifier?
>What are the data types, and do they need to be changed?
>What data mining techniques will you use?
>For example do I need to link my data files and if so, what is that linking field?
>How will you evaluate the results of the data mining analysis?
>How will you get the most from the information you obtain from DM?
>The best way to answer these questions is to follow a structured approach.
>The Cross Industry Standard Process for Data Mining; called CRISP-DM, provides an appropriate framework to capture these aspects.
> CRISP-DM is a framework for the Data Mining process that describes a commonly used approach to tackle problems.
>The CRISP-DM reference model encourages best practices and offers organizations the structure needed to realize better and faster results from Data Mining.
>The Data Mining lifecycle consists of six phases.
>The sequence of phases is not firm and it is often necessary to move forwards and backwards during the process.
>The outcome of each phase is the input into the next one as indicated by the arrows.
>The outer cycle represents the cyclical nature of Data Mining itself
> the lessons learned from a deployed solution could trigger new business questions. In summary, the CRISP-DM phases are:
>\tBusiness Understanding\t
>\tData Understanding\t
>\tData Preparation\t
>\tModeling\t
>\tEvaluation/Validation\t
>\tDeployment\t
>Click on each part of the CRISP_DM to examine the components.
